      "content": "The pandemic era data is certainly compelling due to the massive, temporary nature of the benefit increases. While some economists argue that these large injections of support can foster dependency, others contend that they acted as necessary stabilizers during a supply chain and health crisis. Defining this as an established long-term fact involves complex modeling, as the effects often depend on how those temporary supports transition back to the pre-crisis norms. Ultimately, the long-term economic impact is sensitive to the design and sunset clauses of those specific policy expansions.",
